<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_CrossProductAlgebraicProperties"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Cross product: algebraic properties</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>What do these equations describing algebraic properties of the cross product actually say? â€“ Find details here.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>The cross product operation has the following properties</para.body>
      </para>
      <part.theorem partid="Bilinear">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>For arbitrary vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>, and <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math> the following hold</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ (\Vect{u} + \Vect{v}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{y} }\ +\ \CrssPr{ \Vect{v} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ (\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{x} }\ +\ \CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ (t\cdot \Vect{x}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot (\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }) = \CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ (t\cdot \Vect{y}) }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="AntiSymmetric">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>For arbitrary <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>,</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>-\CrssPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>Bilinear</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>Bilinear</caption>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>These three identities together assert that the cross product operation is bilinear. To verify these bilinearity properties, we recall that the determinant operation on  <math>
                     <latex>(2,2)</latex>
                  </math>-matrices is 
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>bilinear</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_DeterminantAlgebraicProperties"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Look up these properties of the determinant operation.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>.
			So we obtain, for example,</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
      <proof.block>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>AntiSymmetric</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>AntiSymmetric</caption>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The antisymmetry property of the cross product follows directly from the 
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>alternating property</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_DeterminantAlgebraicProperties"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Look up these properties of the determinant operation.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>
			of the determinant operation.</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
